lows/code-coverage-improvement.md:159:inventory/profile join (§WF-dynamic-access-workflow).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:161:The code coverage test suite should be physically and logically separate from\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:163:metadata-generation tests as context, but generated coverage tests must be\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:164:written to the coverage-suite root and measured with code-coverage metrics.\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:165:Metadata-generation tests remain the source of dynamic-access and native-image\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:180:operational shape as chunked dynamic-access exhaust state without sharing the\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:181:dynamic-access report schema (§WF-dynamic-access-exhaust-report).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:194:- Did the run preserve existing dynamic-access, metadata, JVM, and native-image\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:210:- selected API coverage targets and their terminal statuses\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:217:evidence from dynamic-access coverage evidence. A PR that improves code\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:218:coverage should not be presented as a dynamic-access coverage fix unless it\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:219:also ran and reported the dynamic-access workflow (§WF-improve-library-coverage).\nforge/docs/workflows/code-coverage-improvement.md:225:inventory builder, a coverage analyzer, a target-state schema, metrics support,\n./skills/README.md:30:It covers new-library metadata PRs, including titles like `[GenAI] Add support for com.fasterxml:classmate:1.5.1 using gpt-5.4`, and encodes the review rules already used in this repository: reject scaffold-only tests, keep test packages separate from library packages so tests do not bypass visibility boundaries, and question metadata coverage claims that are not supported by the diff.\n./skills/README.md:35:It covers compile-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the compile fix, preserve meaningful tests, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:40:It covers JVM runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: keep the diff scoped to the Java runtime fix, preserve meaningful tests and assertions, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:45:It covers native-image runtime-failure repair PRs for existing libraries and applies a lighter review than `library-new-request`: verify the native path is fixed rather than skipped, keep metadata and test changes scoped, and block regressions where dynamic-access coverage drops between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/README.md:52:### `close-human-intervention-and-failing-ci-prs`\n./skills/README.md:54:Closes batches of open pull requests that have the `human-intervention` label or failing CI.\nforge/docs/agent.md:78:coverage-positive automation that uses the least tokens needed for the task.\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:12:5. Human-intervention strictness (§ROADMAP-forge-human-intervention-strictness).\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:13:6. Planned code coverage improvement workflow (§ROADMAP-forge-code-coverage-workflow).\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:54:reachability-repo path, and the existing dynamic-access preservation flag.\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:92:(§WF-improve-library-coverage.2).\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:100:driver, and compatible versions to the ordinary improve-coverage driver\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:101:(§WF-improve-library-coverage.2). The router must not duplicate javac-fix,\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:102:java-run-fix, or coverage setup logic; the selected driver owns normal\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:108:(§WF-native-test-verification-gate) into successful dynamic-access finalization\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:109:(§WF-dynamic-access-workflow). A failing post-iteration native test must drive\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:120:# ROADMAP-forge-human-intervention-strictness: Human-intervention strictness\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:122:This item of §ROADMAP-forge-implementation makes `human-intervention` handling\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:123:match the stricter policy in the spec (§FS-human-intervention-policy).\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:130:review (§FS-automated-pr-review) may skip existing `human-intervention` PRs, and\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:133:requested-changes review. A `human-intervention-fixed` PR must remain the\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:141:`human-intervention`. Other local verification failures should remain normal\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:144:# ROADMAP-forge-code-coverage-workflow: Planned code coverage improvement workflow\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:147:PGO/API-coverage workflow for already-supported libraries\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:148:(§WF-code-coverage-improvement). The workflow must be separate from\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:149:dynamic-access coverage: it targets broader public API and runtime behavior\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:150:using GraalVM PGO runtime profiles, while dynamic-access workflows target\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:151:metadata-relevant calls (§FS-forge-code-coverage-improvement).\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:154:(§WF-code-coverage-improvement-architecture), a PGO profile collector, an API inventory\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:157:coverage suite with separate metrics and review evidence, not in the\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:158:metadata-generation suite (§WF-code-coverage-improvement.2).\nforge/docs/roadmap.md:165:(§WF-code-coverage-improvement.5).\nforge/docs/workflows/native-image-run-fix.md:93:Java fail-fix and dynamic-access workflows. When metrics are added, they must\nforge/prompt_templates/after-successful-iteration/basic_after_success.md:2:- Analyze the existing test methods in the provided file to determine the current coverage.\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:80:- `--strategy-name NAME` select a predefined workflow strategy from `strategies/predefined_strategies.json`. Defaults to `javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.5`.\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:95:- Script results are written in `output/results.json` (§WF-dynamic-access-workflow, §WF-forge-workflow-drivers).\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:101:  [--keep-tests-without-dynamic-access] \\\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:126:- `--keep-tests-without-dynamic-access` keeps generated tests for dynamic-access workflows even if no dynamic-access call sites are covered.\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:262:- JaCoCo XML coverage parser:\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:386:coordinates, active dynamic-access classes, source-context paths, and Gradle\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:421:The `dynamic_access_iterative` workflow improves metadata accuracy by using the `generateDynamicAccessCoverageReport` Gradle task to identify which dynamic-access call sites (reflection, JNI, resources, serialization) are not yet covered by the generated tests. Instead of generating tests blindly, the workflow iterates class-by-class, sending the agent targeted prompts with the exact uncovered call sites for each class. After each attempt, the report is regenerated and coverage deltas are computed to decide whether to retry the same class or move on.\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:452:Composite strategies (run a primary workflow, then refine dynamic-access coverage):\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:456:| `javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4` | `pi` | `javac_iterative` |\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:459:#### Running a dynamic-access strategy\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:482:see `docs/workflows/dynamic-access.md`.\nforge/DEVELOPING.md:502:- Parse JaCoCo XML coverage:\nforge/tests/test_make_pr_ni_run_fix.py:36:                patch.object(make_pr_ni_run_fix, \"collect_version_coverage_metrics\", return_value=(0.0, None)), \\\nforge/tests/test_make_pr_ni_run_fix.py:61:        self.assertIn(\"human-intervention\", labels)\nforge/docs/goals.md:3:Forge should provide coverage-positive automation for the\nforge/docs/goals.md:6:library coverage (§GOAL-maximize-library-coverage), shorten the path from opened\nforge/docs/goals.md:12:# GOAL-maximize-library-coverage: Maximize library coverage\nforge/docs/goals.md:14:Forge should make supported JVM library coverage as high as practical. It should\nforge/docs/goals.md:15:add metadata and tests for unsupported libraries, improve coverage for\nforge/docs/goals.md:31:coverage, and reviewability. It should use the least tokens and compute needed\nforge/tests/test_make_pr_improve_coverage.py:12:from git_scripts.make_pr_improve_coverage import (\nforge/tests/test_make_pr_improve_coverage.py:79:            \"git_scripts.make_pr_improve_coverage._status_paths\",\nforge/tests/test_make_pr_improve_coverage.py:96:            \"git_scripts.make_pr_improve_coverage._status_paths\",\n./forge/prompt_templates/fix-java-run/initial-with-sources.md:15:- Test that is fixed must maintain functional coverage. Never simplify the test to the point of triviality.\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:15:fallback §WF-basic-iterative), dynamic-access generation\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:16:(§WF-dynamic-access-workflow), Java failure repair\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:19:(§WF-native-metadata-tracing), dynamic-access coverage improvement\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:20:(§WF-improve-library-coverage), and planned code coverage improvement\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:21:(§WF-code-coverage-improvement).\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:36:are used for that run. Shared utilities provide source context, dynamic-access\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:47:layer (§ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec). The planned code coverage workflow\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:48:follows the same split (§WF-code-coverage-improvement-architecture).\nforge/docs/workflows/architecture.md:101:example, retry budgets, source-context selections, dynamic-access limits, and\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:20:makes the test compile and pass, and then improve dynamic-access coverage for\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:21:the new version through the composite phase (§WF-improve-library-coverage). The\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:26:A repaired test must keep meaningful functional coverage; the workflow must not\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:72:- `--javac`: `javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4`\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:73:- `--java-run`: `java_run_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4`\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:99:    Failed -- nativeTest or none --> Coverage[Composite dynamic-access<br/>coverage phase]\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:116:6. After the JVM fix succeeds, run the dynamic-access coverage phase for the new\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:118:   the new version better covered (§WF-improve-library-coverage,\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:141:It is the same component the dynamic-access workflow drives per class, here\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:152:- Improved dynamic-access coverage for the new version from the composite phase\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:153:  (§WF-improve-library-coverage).\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:154:- Durable logs for the initial Gradle run, each agent turn, the coverage phase,\nforge/docs/workflows/java-fail-fix.md:231:- Test that is fixed must maintain functional coverage. Never simplify the test to the point of triviality.\nforge/docs/orchestration-scripts.md:16:`library-update-request` route to dynamic-access generation\nforge/docs/orchestration-scripts.md:17:(§WF-dynamic-access-workflow) and coverage improvement\nforge/docs/orchestration-scripts.md:18:(§WF-improve-library-coverage); `fails-javac-compile` and `fails-java-run` route\nforge/docs/orchestration-scripts.md:74:Successful or chunk-ready runs (§WF-chunked-dynamic-access-pr-linking) proceed to\nforge/docs/orchestration-scripts.md:98:queue label, plus PRs carrying `human-intervention-fixed`, and selects only\nforge/docs/orchestration-scripts.md:100:not still blocked by `human-intervention`. PRs labeled `human-intervention` are\nforge/docs/orchestration-scripts.md:101:skipped until a maintainer marks them `human-intervention-fixed`, at which point\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-native-image-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes a native-image runtime failure for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the runtime/native fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair metadata or tests after an existing library version compiles and builds a native image, but the native image fails when the test runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library is already supported, so the goal is to restore native-image behavior for a newer version while preserving existing dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:19:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:53:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:55:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - If metadata fixes make the native run pass but the dynamic-access ratio drops, ask for restored coverage first. Passing native execution is not enough by itself.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:67:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:76:   - If CI is flaky but the diff and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:84:- Dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previous and new tested versions, or any apparent drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:90:- The fix makes native execution pass by skipping the failing native path, disabling assertions, or removing coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:91:- Dynamic-access coverage drops without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:100:- The API or native runtime change is plausible but the PR does not explain why a coverage drop is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:107:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-native-image-run-fail/SKILL.md:109:- For native skips: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./forge/prompt_templates/fix-javac/initial-with-sources.md:14:- Test that is fixed must maintain functional coverage. Never simplify the test to the point of triviality.\nforge/README.md:102:python3 ai_workflows/drivers/improve_library_coverage.py --coordinates <group:artifact:version>\nforge/prompt_templates/initial/basic_initial.md:1:Role: You are an expert JVM test engineer specializing in high-coverage integration testing for external libraries.\n./forge/prompt_templates/after-successful-iteration/codex_after_success.md:1:Role: You are an expert JVM test engineer specializing in high-coverage integration testing for external libraries.\nforge/git_scripts/make_pr_java_run_fix.py:188:- Library coverage percentage: {metrics.get(\"code_coverage_percent\", 0)}\nforge/git_scripts/make_pr_java_run_fix.py:191:- Previous library version coverage percentage: {metrics.get(\"previous_library_coverage_percent\", 0)}\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-javac-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR that fixes Java compilation failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the compile fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair test sources or test dependencies after an existing library is bumped and the new version no longer compiles with the old test code. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library already exists, so the goal is to preserve working coverage across the version update rather than prove a brand-new metadata contribution from scratch.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:17:- Be more relaxed than `library-new-request`: do not reject only because a test resembles older coverage, stays in an existing package layout, or contains compatibility branches for multiple supported versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:18:- Do not accept changes that remove meaningful test coverage just to make `javac` pass.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:54:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:56:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:57:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:67:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/package change.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:74:   - Prefer seeing the full target `test` lane green because a compile fix can still reduce runtime or native coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:76:   - If CI is flaky but the diff and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:84:- Dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previous and new tested versions, or any apparent drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:90:- The fix makes compilation pass by weakening or bypassing the test instead of adapting it to the changed API while preserving meaningful coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:92:- Dynamic-access coverage drops without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:100:- The API change is plausible but the PR does not explain why a coverage drop is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:107:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:109:- For deleted coverage: say that the PR fixes compilation by removing coverage and should instead adapt the test to the new API.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:110:- For native skips that does not depend on the open-ended dynamic class loading: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-javac-fail/SKILL.md:121:- Bad compile repair that removes coverage:\n./forge/prompt_templates/after-successful-iteration/basic_after_success.md:2:- Analyze the existing test methods in the provided file to determine the current coverage.\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:66:from ai_workflows.drivers.improve_library_coverage import (\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:67:    main as run_improve_library_coverage_workflow,\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:105:from git_scripts.make_pr_improve_coverage import (\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:106:    build_pull_request_preview as build_improve_coverage_pull_request_preview,\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:108:    main as run_make_pr_improve_coverage,\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:110:from utility_scripts.dynamic_access_report import load_dynamic_access_coverage_report\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:206:LABEL_HUMAN_INTERVENTION = \"human-intervention\"\n./forge/forge_metadata.py:207:LABEL_HUMAN_INTERVENTION_FIXED = \"hum